    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26c.83-84_0001"/>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        State Hospital
                        Fulton, Missouri
                        December 21, '58.
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Dr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>University of Missouri</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I have your letter of December 3 and I thank you for your kindness in replying.</p>
                
                <p>The joke is on us that we didn't discover that you had changed your time of the telecasting and were, in reality, still telecasting. Our ward (that is, we patients on our ward) leaves the ward a little before five o'clock to go to the cafeteria for supper and stay about half an hour. That leaves us out completely on hearing your program. But we are with you in spirit, anyway, and our every good wish follows you.</p>
                
                <p>I feel flattered that you say you agree with what I say about education, neighborliness, and so forth, and that, as you see the matter, I am certainly right. I have been hoping to be able to make an impression on
                
                <fw type="curatorial">83</fw>
                    
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26c.83-84_0002"/>
                
                    people with my expression of my opinions and ideas. I am a social reformer at heart &#8212; of necessity, because of the way my life went. I want to do much to help build up the schools, provide better and more-rounded-out schooling for all, and to help others to see the necessity of providing a proper curriculum <add>(including religion<del>)</del>- a belief in God + a feeling of responsibility toward, God for one's actions)</add> so that children may grow up normal and able to cope with life's problems &#8212; alas I want to do much to help the mentally and physically ill or affected, to keep them on their feet and at their jobs or in school, and out of hospitals. That is a big order but I think that is what should be done. We just can't keep <del>up</del><add>on</add> ruining people's lives and then locking them up in hospitals like this to get them out of the way at home &#8212; it isn't right and it's no fun for those who are locked up! I might, for effect, quote here what Patrick Henry said "Give me liberty or give me death!"</p>
                
                <p>I wish you, Dr. Neihardt, a happy holiday season &#8212; a Merry Christmas and a Happy New Year!</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely,</salute>
                
                    <signed>Rosalind Kolb</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
